table-0542-197.pgTitle: 2009–10 NCAA Division I men's basketball season
table-0542-197.caption: Coaching changes
data: Peterson left his second stint with Appalachian State after one season to move across the state to UNC Wilmington.
Lebo was fired after missing the NCAA tournament in each of his six seasons. He went on to be hired by East Carolina.
Skinner was fired after 13 years at BC.
Purnell left for the DePaul job after taking Clemson to three straight NCAA Tournaments for only the second time in school history.
Bzdelik left to work for old Northwestern colleague Ron Wellman at Wake Forest.
Jones left to become Associate Head Coach at Boston College.
Donahue left for the Boston College job after guiding Cornell to three straight Ivy League crowns and an NCAA Sweet 16 appearance.
Altman left to become Head Coach at Oregon.
McCarthy stepped down after three seasons to take a fundraising position in the university's athletic department, specifically aimed at an on-campus basketball practice facility.
Whittenburg was fired after a 1–4 start.
Scruggs was fired after 15 years at Gardner-Webb.
Kowalczyk left for the Toledo job.
Leibovitz resigned with four years left on his contract to become top assistant at Penn.
Kearney was fired after only one year.
Collins retired in the Summer before the 2010–11 season.
Lickliter was fired after a three-year tenure that saw three losing seasons, with four players transferring out of Iowa after the 2008–09 season and a fifth leaving during this season.
McDermott made the unusual move to Creighton and the MVC and was replaced by Hoiberg, who grew up in Ames and starred for the Cyclones, where he became known as "The Mayor".

Lee was fired after six seasons in Lafayette and a 13–16 record in his final season. The Ragin' Cajuns program was plagued by academic problems that resulted in lost scholarships in each of Lee's three final seasons.
Early left to become an assistant at South Carolina.
Miller was fired after a 0–7 start and replaced by former Penn star (and assistant coach) Allen.
Rice left after three straight 20+ win seasons to take the head coach job at Rutgers.
Hill resigned after a lack of progress in the program, including the transfer of star Mike Rosario after the season's end.
Marlin left to take the Louisiana-Lafayette opening.
Siena promoted top assistant Buonaguro after Iowa hired away McCaffery.
Speraw, the school's winningest coach, was fired after a disappointing 15–17 season. The Knights had not made the NCAA Tournament since 2005.
Moss was reassigned to a new position in the UNCW athletic department after a 7–14 start.
Barbee left for Auburn and the SEC.
Deane was fired after a 5–26 season.
Gaudio was fired after a 1–6 postseason record in his three years.
Brownell left for the Clemson job.

table-0542-811.caption: (Open World)
data: Soldado: asesino de la patria Hombre, rechaza el uniforme que denigra. Yo sé de miles de botas que se hunden en la tierra nuestra, destrozándola.
Soldier: murderer of the fatherland Man, reject the uniform that defames. I know of thousands of boots that sink in our land, destroying it.
Yo sé de la marinería borracha y sádica que como una avalancha de blanco estiércol se riega por calles y plazas vomitando su negro sello de piratas.
I know about the sadistic and drunken seamanship that as an avalanche of white manure spreads through the streets and plazas vomiting its black seal of pirates.
Yo sé de los aviones que ametrallaron nuestros tejados en un día de octubre. Aquel horrible desprecio que llovía en fuego sembrando dolores profundos.
I know of the airplanes that machine-gunned our rooftops in a day of October. That horrible contempt that rained in fire sowing deep pains.

data: In the 17th Century the open Spanish royal crown set upon the shield.
Circa 1650 stars set 2, 2, 2 and 1 changing to 3, 2 and 2. Consoles became a common external ornament.
In 1967 the griffin and the civic crown were removed.

In 1982 the heraldic open crown used by Franco's regime was replaced by the older open royal crown. The design of the elements has become more simplified and the escutcheon shape has been changed too.

data: The mahjong club goes to a mountain retreat for mahjong training camp. The first day is used for leisure. The next day, Hisa assigns the first years (excluding Kyōtarō) special tasks. Saki plays mahjong online but struggles to win. The online player Nodoka trains with the others to work more with actual tiles. Yūki struggles with score tracking and does math drills. Eventually, everyone plays each other. After a few rounds, Yūki vents about losing so much against Nodoka, Saki and Hisa. For support, the club president recounts her first-year, when she was the sole member of the club but remained patient. She expresses gratification for the new members. Yūki continues to play, and manages a win. The next day, Yūki, Nodoka and Saki go to see the nearby waterfall.

After arriving at the tournament area, Saki gets separated from her friends; and the current national junior high school champion, Nodoka, is hounded by reporters. On the other hand, Saki crosses paths with the members of Ryūmonbuchi (minus Koromo). As they pass each other, the Ryūmonbuchi team senses a familiar aura flowing from Saki, an aura similar to that of Koromo. They initially mistake her for Nodoka, until Tōka indicates otherwise. A couple more steps and Saki suddenly trips, and Jun muses that there is no way another mahjong player of Koromo's level could possibly exist. After Saki rejoins the group, Hisa reveals the player order: Yūki, Mako, herself, Nodoka, and Saki. Competition begins with Kiyosumi initially underestimated, Yūki wins many hands and dominates. Afterwards, Mako and Hisa also make quick work of their opponents, ending with a commanding lead. For Nodoka's round, she draws the attention of a large audience.

Yūki flunks her math midterm and must take a makeup test, where failure will make her unable to attend the camp. Therefore, Saki and Nodoka help her study. The match soon turns into a heated battle between Ako, Sera and Shiraitodai's Takami Shibuya, who prepares to use her 'Harvest Time' ability.

As the third match ends with a play from Takami, Sera mentions to Ako how things may have been worse if Takami was the last dealer. The fourth match soon begins with Arata and Hiroko up against Shiraitodai's Seiko Matano and Shindouji's Mairu Shirouzu. During the match, Mairu puts limitations on her hands so that they'll be worth double when her partner, Himeko Tsuruta, plays in the following match. Meanwhile, Koromo and Hajime visit Saki, where they talk about the time they played with Achiga. Mairu wins the majority of hands, whilst Hiroko manages to use Seiko's weaknesses against her. As Arata also manages to make some wins, she recalls how Harue decided to appoint her club president, thinking of the feelings she is carrying to try and clear the semi-finals that Harue could not. As the match comes to its climax with Mairu scoring a powerful hand, Toki wakes up in hospital.
